{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774458212,"nonce":"c5Z5gUUzAGSDkmqsX4dTGF6jdig=","title":"Part 2 analysis: SISU sensitivity via Jacobian decomposition","message":"Umbrella: 0af472c (Part 2)\n\n**Motivation:** Quantify how sensitive each network unit and the overall dynamics are to the SISU input, and how this sensitivity is distributed across the state space. The input Jacobian dh/du decomposed by input channel reveals whether SISU has a privileged or diffuse effect on the network dynamics, and whether this changes with training robustness level.\n\n**Approach:**\n1. Compute the full input Jacobian J_u = dh(t+1)/du(t) at steady state and during reaching (infrastructure exists in `fps_steady` and `plant_perts`).\n2. Decompose J_u by input channel using `RNNInputChannels` (SISU, position, velocity, goal position, goal velocity) and `split_by`.\n3. For the SISU column(s): compute norms per unit to get a SISU sensitivity profile. Compare with readout weights to test whether SISU-sensitive units are in the potent or null space.\n4. Compute the SVD of each input channel block to characterize the gain structure. Track how the SISU gain (max singular value of the SISU Jacobian block) varies with SISU level and training condition.\n5. Cross-reference with `unit_perts` results: do units with high SISU Jacobian norm also show large behavioral effects under stimulation?\n\n**Status:** No dedicated module yet. The `fps_steady` module already computes `steady_state_jac-u_svd` and `unit_perts` has commented-out `jac-u-ss` infrastructure with `jacobian_input_channel_norms`. This issue is about consolidating and extending that work into a focused SISU sensitivity analysis.\n\n**References:** Maheswaranathan et al. (2019) for Jacobian-based RNN analysis.","files":null}]}